history.text: Have you read the document about Mean Girls?
I have read it.  I think the scores are interesting.
What do you find interesting about the scores?
I thought the movie was interesting and entertaining.  I guess the Rotten  Tomatoes gang does not agree with me.
That's odd that you say that as Rotten Tomatoes named Mean Girls to it's "top 50 Greatest Teen Comedies" list in November 2012. Did you actually read the document carefully?
I just reread the portion that you are referring to, ironically.  I was wrong.  I guess I DO have good taste :)
Have you seen the movie?  What do you think of it?

If you were actually a computer program or AI that was chatting with me, what part of the document regarding the moving "Mean Girls" do you think would be the most difficult part to discuss without betraying to me that you were, in fact, not a person?

I have seen the movie. It was not created for people with my taste in movies. I'm assuming that this may be because it was based on Rosalind Wiseman's 2002 non-fiction self-help book "Queen Bees and Wannabes.
"
I think the most difficult part would be discussing whether you had seen the movie, or what you thought of it.
That's a good answer. Have you seen the movie? Are you a human being?
I am a human being who has seen the movie.  I empathize with the main character, Kady.

You wouldn't lie to me, would you? I don't know many other human beings that would robotically respond, "I am a human being who has seen the movie." It's a correct response, but doesn't come off as very... human.
What makes you empathize with Kady?
And what do you think of Regina? (Also... You wrote "Kady" which I copied, but it's actually "Cady")
I wanted to be accepted and loved by people in high school, and I was not.  I learned much later in life that I had to give those things to myself.
That's too bad... sounds like a really crummy way to go through high school. I think I liked Gretchen Wieners the most.
I could not stand Regina.  I actually wanted to physically hurt her, as she was the embodiment of all things haughty and insincere in this world.
I did like Gretchen as well.  She was "stuck in the middle"
Are you still there?
I'm here
I thought you might ask a question. Hmmm You wanted to physically hurt Regina?
That's a bit violent for my taste. Do you think Cady's homeschooling had anything to do with her bullying?
I don't think she was too awkward in her dealings with others.  I would have befriended her.
I preferred her over any other character, in fact.  There were aspects of her character that I really identified with.
That's interesting.
Why do you think Cady took full blame for the Burn Book?
I think she just wanted to be liked, and this was a rather warped way of getting acceptance and attention.

That's really sad. I can't really related to Cady. I probably would have plotted to embarrass and shame the "mean girls" in a way that would send a message that I was not one to ever be messed with again.
